---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Callout from '../components/Callout.astro';
import { url } from '../lib/url';

const title = 'The 2026 Blueprint';
const description =
  'A synthesis of the two source documents Groundwork is built from. The Blueprint covers the model and the practice; the Playbook covers operational standards and tool-specific patterns.';
---

<Base title={title} description={description}>
  <div class="container blueprint">
    <h1>The 2026 Context Engineering Blueprint</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      A synthesis of the two source documents Groundwork is built from. The
      first covers the model and the practice; the second covers operational
      standards and tool-specific patterns. Both are reproduced in full in
      the repo.
    </p>

    <Callout label="The full texts" tone="ember">
      <p>
        The full sources live in the repo with their references and citations:
        <a href="https://github.com/IgniticAB/groundwork/blob/main/AI-First%20R%26D%20Context%20Engineering%20101.md">
          AI-First R&amp;D Context Engineering 101.md
        </a>
        and
        <a href="https://github.com/IgniticAB/groundwork/blob/main/AI%20Agent%20Context%20Engineering%20Best%20Practices.md">
          AI Agent Context Engineering Best Practices.md</a>.
        This page is the navigable summary, with anchors the rest of the site
        links back to.
      </p>
    </Callout>

    <h2>The premise</h2>
    <p>
      In 2026, the bottleneck on AI-assisted engineering is no longer model
      capability, it is the <em>context wall</em>: the limit of how
      effectively an AI agent can reason over a codebase without being
      overwhelmed by noise or misguided by ambiguity. Context engineering has
      replaced prompt engineering as the foundational discipline. The
      Anthropic 2026 Agentic Coding Trends Report names it as the single most
      important skill shift for developers; structured context layers have
      been shown to cut reasoning drift and computational latency by up to
      86% in published benchmarks.
    </p>
    <p>
      The two source documents converge on the same diagnosis from different
      angles. The Blueprint takes the architectural view (layers, lifecycle,
      cognitive debt); the Playbook takes the operational view (rule
      composition, tool-specific configurations, governance). Together they
      cover the model, the practice, and the operational standard.
    </p>

    <h2 id="five-layer">The five-layer context stack</h2>
    <p>
      A mature 2026 context strategy is built on a five-layer stack that
      ensures the AI agent has the situational awareness it needs to act with
      precision.
    </p>
    <figure class="persistence-axis">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 600 140" role="img" aria-labelledby="pa-title" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
        <title id="pa-title">Five context layers placed along a persistence axis from transient (left) to static (right).</title>
        <line class="pa-axis" x1="40" y1="90" x2="555" y2="90" />

        <g class="pa-dots">
          <circle class="pa-dot" cx="40"  cy="90" r="7" />
          <circle class="pa-dot" cx="170" cy="90" r="7" />
          <circle class="pa-dot" cx="300" cy="90" r="7" />
          <circle class="pa-dot" cx="430" cy="90" r="7" />
          <circle class="pa-dot" cx="555" cy="90" r="7" />
        </g>

        <g class="pa-names">
          <text x="40"  y="55" text-anchor="middle">SESSION</text>
          <text x="170" y="55" text-anchor="middle">CODEBASE</text>
          <text x="300" y="55" text-anchor="middle">TOOLING</text>
          <text x="430" y="55" text-anchor="middle">PROJECT</text>
          <text x="555" y="55" text-anchor="middle">SYSTEM</text>
        </g>

        <text class="pa-end-label" x="40"  y="125" text-anchor="start">transient</text>
        <text class="pa-end-label" x="555" y="125" text-anchor="end">static</text>
      </svg>
      <figcaption>
        Five layers, ordered by how long their contents live. Deep dive on the
        <a href={url('foundation/five-layer-stack/')}>foundation page</a>.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Used correctly, the layers prevent the common 2025 failure mode where
      an agent would fix a local bug but inadvertently refactor adjacent
      code in a way that violated project conventions. Each layer gets its
      own retention strategy and its own update cadence.
    </p>
    <p><a href={url('foundation/five-layer-stack/')}>→ Foundation page: The five-layer stack</a></p>

    <h2 id="cognitive-debt">Cognitive debt, the hidden risk</h2>
    <p>
      The most pervasive risk in the rapid adoption of AI-generated code is
      the accumulation of cognitive debt: the gap between a system's evolving
      structure and the team's shared understanding of how and why that
      system works. AI agents reduce technical debt by automating refactors
      and test generation. They simultaneously accelerate cognitive debt by
      producing code faster than humans can internalise it.
    </p>
    <p>
      Cognitive debt manifests through "cognitive surrender": developers
      adopt AI outputs with minimal scrutiny, bypassing deliberate reasoning.
      Code functions and passes tests, but the human responsible for it has
      "lost the plot". The danger is invisibility: unlike a linter, cognitive
      debt only surfaces during a crisis.
    </p>
    <p>The four practices high-performing teams have converged on:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Atomic interaction and review.</strong> Large features broken into small, atomic changes. Each reviewed individually.</li>
      <li><strong>Externalising intent.</strong> Architecture Decision Records and "negative space documentation": explicitly recording what was <em>not</em> done and why.</li>
      <li><strong>Mandatory Plan Mode.</strong> Before any implementation, the agent enters a plan that serves as a contract.</li>
      <li><strong>Verification-first workflows.</strong> Rock-solid tests, linters, browser-based agents. The agent self-corrects against verification.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><a href={url('foundation/cognitive-debt/')}>→ Foundation page: Cognitive debt</a></p>

    <h2 id="context-rot">Context Rot: four failure modes in long sessions</h2>
    <p>
      Even with good context files in place, long agent sessions degrade.
      Conversation history accumulates, the runtime compacts it, and the
      original rules get summarised into vague generalisations. The same
      agent that wrote pristine type-safe code in hour one starts writing
      unannotated functions in hour four. The Playbook names four distinct
      rot patterns, each with its own mitigation.
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Rot</th><th>What it looks like</th><th>Mitigation</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Poisoning</strong></td>
          <td>The agent uses deprecated APIs, outdated parameters, or stale syntax.</td>
          <td>Version-controlled deprecation logs; explicit "do not use X, use Y" rules; stale-context checks.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Distraction</strong></td>
          <td>Irrelevant rules fire while the agent is editing in an unrelated area.</td>
          <td>Scoped rules; strict token budgets in always-apply rules; split-file architecture.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Confusion</strong></td>
          <td>Similar-but-distinct objects get conflated (<code>User</code> vs <code>UserAccount</code>).</td>
          <td>Precise namespace mapping; before/after code examples; ADRs that name the distinction.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Clash</strong></td>
          <td>Two rules in active memory contradict; output paralysis or silent "last wins".</td>
          <td>Cross-file consistency checks; one canonical source; centralised governance.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      The most common rot at hour two is Distraction; at hour four it is
      Poisoning (the original rules have been summarised away). Frequent
      session clears (<code>/clear</code> or equivalent) force the agent to
      reload fresh configurations from disk.
    </p>

    <h2 id="contextops">Maintainable architecture: ContextOps</h2>
    <p>
      A maintainable 2026 architecture is "AI-readable" without sacrificing
      human clarity. The discipline is increasingly codified as
      <strong>ContextOps</strong>: a systematic lifecycle for context
      management that mirrors the DevOps revolution.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Build.</strong> Automated tools scan repositories to detect patterns and generate initial standards and commands.</li>
      <li><strong>Distribute.</strong> Rules generated in the specific formats each tool requires.</li>
      <li><strong>Maintain.</strong> Pre-commit hooks and CI checks validate context files are updated alongside code changes.</li>
      <li><strong>Update.</strong> Context evolution handled through delta updates rather than full rewrites, preserving historical knowledge.</li>
      <li><strong>Measure.</strong> Track the conformity rate of generated code against defined standards to identify where context is failing.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Context-modular patterns standardised in 2026: <strong>scoped
      rules</strong> with file-pattern frontmatter, <strong>agent persona
      specialisation</strong> (the "copilot squad"), and
      <strong>persistent project context</strong> (<code>AGENTS.md</code>
      with <code>CLAUDE.md</code> as a symlink) at the repo root.
    </p>
    <p>
      Industry data: 59% of developers run three or more AI coding assistants
      in parallel; without ContextOps, parallel use raises codebase
      duplication by up to 4x and drives shipping confidence below 30%. The
      countervailing pattern is exactly what the lifecycle prescribes:
      treat context as code, version it, peer-review it, and validate it in
      CI.
    </p>
    <p><a href={url('foundation/contextops-lifecycle/')}>→ Foundation page: The ContextOps lifecycle</a></p>

    <h2 id="split-file">The split-file architecture</h2>
    <p>
      The single biggest behavioural finding in the Playbook: <strong>do not
      let <code>CLAUDE.md</code> become a dumping ground</strong>. Because
      Claude Code (and similar agents) treat the file as mutable, they
      append session-specific rules over time. The root file bloats, model
      attention is diluted, and after several weeks the file no longer
      functions as a stable contract.
    </p>
    <p>The corrective pattern is structural:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Lean root.</strong> <code>AGENTS.md</code> stays under
        roughly 400 tokens (~80 lines). It is the canonical cross-tool
        source.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Split rule directory.</strong> Stable, long-form, or per-area
        conventions live in <code>.claude/rules/&lt;NN&gt;-&lt;name&gt;.md</code>.
        A numeric prefix sets load order.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Symlink.</strong> <code>CLAUDE.md</code> is a symlink to
        <code>AGENTS.md</code>. One edit feeds both Anthropic and OpenAI
        orchestrators. On environments without symlink support, a two-file
        fallback works alongside a parity check in the pre-commit hook.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <pre><code>AGENTS.md                       ← lean entry point
CLAUDE.md -&gt; AGENTS.md          ← symlink
.claude/rules/
  00-conventions.md
  10-style-imports.md
  30-verification.md
  50-frontend-tailwind.md
  70-secrets.md</code></pre>
    <p>
      <a href={url('foundation/good-practices/')}>→ Foundation page: Good
      practices § split-file architecture</a>.
      <a href={url('commands/init/')}><code>init</code></a> sets this up
      by default and asks the symlink-vs-two-files question explicitly.
    </p>

    <h2 id="boundary-tiers">Three-tier boundary layout</h2>
    <p>
      The older "out-of-bounds" framing is one bucket. The Playbook proposes
      three explicit tiers, which sharply reduce scope creep:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Always.</strong> Things the agent does without asking (run fast verification, regenerate per-harness files when conventions change).</li>
      <li><strong>Ask first.</strong> Things the agent proposes before doing (multi-file changes, dependency additions, CI changes, public-API edits).</li>
      <li><strong>Never.</strong> Hard forbids (generated paths, vendored upstream, anything inside <code>&lt;!-- CE:PRESERVE --&gt;</code> tags).</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      State all three explicitly in <code>.context/conventions.md</code> and
      in the per-harness files. The "ask first" tier is the most often
      missing one; it is also the one that prevents the most scope creep.
      For code regions that must not be edited at all, wrap them in HTML
      preservation tags with a one-line rationale.
    </p>

    <h2 id="harnesses">The 2026 toolchain</h2>
    <p>
      Four dominant tools, each effective only to the extent the context
      fed to them is well-engineered.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Claude Code.</strong> The autonomous CLI specialist for
        high-autonomy tasks like complex refactoring and git-intensive
        workflows. Best practices: <code>/init</code> as foundation,
        verification loops in every prompt, <code>/compact</code> for long
        sessions, CLI access only with strict security boundaries. Treat
        <code>CLAUDE.md</code> as a lean root that loads
        <code>.claude/rules/</code> via <code>@imports</code>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Cursor.</strong> The context-aware IDE. Daily driver for
        most developers. Modern <code>.cursor/rules/*.mdc</code> with YAML
        frontmatter. Four trigger levels with explicit body-length budgets:
        Always Apply (&lt;200 words), Auto-Attached (200–500), Agent-Requested
        (500–800), Manual (no cap). Sizing rules to the trigger is the
        single biggest determinant of Cursor token-cost performance.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>GitHub Copilot.</strong> Tiered ingestion:
        <code>.github/copilot-instructions.md</code> for repo-wide,
        <code>.github/instructions/*.instructions.md</code> for path-scoped,
        and <code>.github/agents/*.agent.md</code> for domain-specific
        agent profiles invoked via <code>/agent &lt;name&gt;</code>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Windsurf.</strong> Cascade-powered IDE with semantic
        workspace indexing. Rules in <code>.windsurfrules</code> (6,000 char
        limit) or <code>.windsurf/rules/</code> (12,000 char total). Dynamic
        cross-session facts auto-persist to <code>.windsurfmemories</code>;
        treat that file as agent-managed.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p><a href={url('foundation/harness-reference/')}>→ Foundation page: Harness reference</a></p>

    <h2 id="windsurf">Windsurf and the M-Query pipeline</h2>
    <p>
      Windsurf's distinct contribution is the multi-layered assembly
      pipeline: global rules + workspace rules + persistent memories +
      active editor selection + <code>@-command</code> references + flow
      context, all trimmed to the target model's window. The agent maintains
      cross-session context over weeks without manual configuration updates;
      developers contribute static <code>.windsurfrules</code> and Cascade
      auto-writes architectural discoveries to <code>.windsurfmemories</code>.
      The division between human-authored Rules and agent-authored Memories
      is the operational pattern worth borrowing even on non-Windsurf
      harnesses: keep the contract static and human-reviewed; let
      observations flow into a separate, agent-owned log.
    </p>

    <h2 id="management">Managing an AI-first R&amp;D department</h2>
    <p>
      Operating an R&amp;D department in 2026 requires a shift from measuring
      "lines of code" to measuring <em>architectural consistency</em> and
      <em>systemic health</em>. Data from the 2026 State of AI-First
      Operations Report shows a measurable gap between high-performing
      organisations and underperformers, driven primarily by tool
      consolidation, ROI measurement frequency, and tracking the business
      impact of AI.
    </p>
    <p>The Playbook adds a phased adoption framework:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Audit.</strong> Map existing context files across repositories. Reveals quality disparity and unshared individual practices.</li>
      <li><strong>Standardise.</strong> Convert discoveries into team-wide reference templates.</li>
      <li><strong>Govern.</strong> Pre-commit hooks and CI validation enforce that context updates ship with the code changes they describe.</li>
      <li><strong>Scale.</strong> Onboard teams to the standard; measure ROI; iterate.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>The role shifts:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>The Orchestrator role.</strong> Engineers reskilled to act as agent coordinators, focusing on high-level design and quality evaluation rather than tactical implementation.</li>
      <li><strong>Surge staffing.</strong> With context formalised, onboarding times collapse. Organisations can "surge" talent onto a project by feeding the existing context into the agentic team. Full productivity within hours rather than weeks.</li>
      <li><strong>Democratisation.</strong> Agentic tools enable non-technical stakeholders to build self-service tools, shifting R&amp;D's focus toward providing secure infrastructure and context playbooks for the rest of the company.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="mcp">MCP, the protocols of the new perimeter</h2>
    <p>
      The Model Context Protocol has emerged as the "USB-C port for AI",
      providing a standard interface for connecting models to real-world data
      and tools. In 2026 it is the backbone of any serious AI-first
      architecture.
    </p>
    <p>Three primitives:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Resources.</strong> Read-only data sources (e.g. PostgreSQL URIs) the model can access for context.</li>
      <li><strong>Tools.</strong> Executable actions with defined JSON-schema inputs that the model can invoke to trigger side effects.</li>
      <li><strong>Prompts.</strong> Reusable templates the host application can render.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Three non-negotiables for security and governance:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Least-privilege binding.</strong> Agents granted only the minimum permissions required. Read-only context servers physically separated from mutation-capable tool servers.</li>
      <li><strong>Human-in-the-loop (HITL).</strong> High-stakes actions like production deployments or destructive queries must require explicit human approval via a consent UI.</li>
      <li><strong>Centralised auditing.</strong> Every tool invocation (agent identity, parameters, response) logged for real-time alerting on unusual patterns or unauthorised access.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><a href={url('foundation/mcp-principles/')}>→ Foundation page: MCP principles</a></p>

    <h2 id="pruning">Context pruning: overcoming the context wall</h2>
    <p>
      To handle the context wall problem, 2026 R&amp;D departments have moved
      beyond simple token limits toward task-aware, adaptive pruning.
      <strong>SWE-Pruner</strong> uses a lightweight model to selectively skim
      source code, capturing the raw context and filtering it down to lines
      relevant to the agent's stated goal. <strong>Semantic
      de-duplication</strong> uses embeddings to detect and merge
      semantically similar instructions in persistent context files.
      <strong>Incremental delta updates</strong> (the ACE framework) perform
      localised updates that accumulate new insights while preserving
      historical knowledge.
    </p>
    <p>
      A complementary pattern from the Playbook: <strong>Just-In-Time data
      retrieval</strong>. Instead of overloading the context window with
      complete schemas or documentation libraries, the agent receives a
      lightweight metadata index and queries detailed files only when
      actively editing them. The "librarian" model prevents cognitive
      overload, reduces token cost, and eliminates context clutter.
    </p>

    <h2 id="good-practices">Good practices and high-risk anti-patterns</h2>

    <h3>Practices to embrace</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Behaviorally-anchored rules.</strong> Every rule names a specific technology, command, or pattern; never "use good judgment".</li>
      <li><strong>Negative space documentation.</strong> Documenting rejected paths prevents the AI from suggesting them repeatedly.</li>
      <li><strong>Defensive commits.</strong> Creating a git checkpoint before refactoring protects against data loss during long sessions.</li>
      <li><strong>Interface-first development.</strong> Defining types before implementation prevents the AI from building sprawling, incorrect abstractions.</li>
      <li><strong>Verification-driven logic.</strong> Providing test commands allows the agent to self-correct.</li>
      <li><strong>Standardised <code>/init</code> commands.</strong> Automating the creation of context files ensures every repo starts with a baseline of rules.</li>
      <li><strong>HTML preservation tags</strong> wrapping human-designed source files so agents cannot modify the wrapped region.</li>
      <li><strong>Human-only commit authorship</strong> as a hard rule: agents propose, humans commit. Keeps version-control accountability uncontaminated.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Anchored vs vague rule examples</h3>
    <p>
      The single most reliable predictor of agent output quality is whether
      the rules tell the agent what to <em>do</em>, naming the specific tool
      or pattern, rather than naming an adjective.
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Category</th><th>Anchored (good)</th><th>Vague (bad)</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Error handling</td>
          <td>Wrap external API calls in try/catch; log via <code>Logger</code>; never swallow exceptions.</td>
          <td>"Write robust error handling."</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Styling</td>
          <td>Tailwind utilities only; conditional classes via <code>cn()</code>; assets in <code>/assets/</code>.</td>
          <td>"Use clean styling patterns."</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Testing</td>
          <td>Vitest; assert on user actions; run <code>npm run test:coverage</code> before staging.</td>
          <td>"Maintain high test coverage."</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Git workflow</td>
          <td>Conventional Commits; one-file scope where reasonable; humans sole authors of record.</td>
          <td>"Commit often with helpful messages."</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Dependencies</td>
          <td>Pin critical packages; named imports; <code>npm run build</code> to verify types on modified modules.</td>
          <td>"Keep dependencies updated."</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Practices to avoid</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Monolithic prompt bloat.</strong> System prompts as a dumping ground for product docs wastes tokens and pushes important context away from the model's attention.</li>
      <li><strong>Vague principles without examples.</strong> "Use good judgment" is useless. Anchor every principle (see table above).</li>
      <li><strong>Placeholder comments.</strong> Never allow <code>// TODO: implement this</code>. Functions are either complete or absent.</li>
      <li><strong>Implicit local assumptions.</strong> The agent does not know your timezone, device, or permissions. State them in the Session layer.</li>
      <li><strong>Over-exposing tools.</strong> Route tools by intent. Every tool description costs tokens and adds attention noise.</li>
      <li><strong>CLAUDE.md as a dumping ground.</strong> See the split-file architecture above for the structural fix.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      <a href={url('foundation/good-practices/')}>→ Foundation page: Good practices</a><br />
      <a href={url('foundation/anti-patterns/')}>→ Foundation page: Anti-patterns</a>
    </p>

    <h2>Actionable strategy for 2026</h2>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Immediate initialisation.</strong> Audit all core repositories and establish <code>AGENTS.md</code> (with <code>CLAUDE.md</code> symlinked) plus <code>.cursor/rules/</code>. Formalises the Project context layer; reduces AI rework by up to 80%.</li>
      <li><strong>Adopt ContextOps.</strong> Implement a versioned lifecycle for context management. Ensure architectural decisions (ADRs) are automatically converted into context files agents can act upon.</li>
      <li><strong>Apply three-tier boundaries.</strong> State Always / Ask first / Never explicitly in conventions. Wrap immutable code regions in HTML preservation tags.</li>
      <li><strong>Harden the MCP layer.</strong> Move integrations to the Model Context Protocol standard. Focus on least-privilege and human-in-the-loop for any destructive operation.</li>
      <li><strong>Incentivise understanding.</strong> Repay cognitive debt by making "understanding" a core metric. Reward teams that prioritise active plan review and rationale documentation over raw feature velocity.</li>
      <li><strong>Scale through orchestration.</strong> Reskill the workforce to act as agent coordinators. Shift engineering focus toward strategic problem decomposition and system-wide architectural consistency.</li>
    </ol>

    <Callout label="The core argument" tone="ember">
      <p>
        Context engineering has shifted the R&amp;D narrative from technology
        in isolation to a strategy of deep integration. <strong>Context is the
        new code, and engineering it is the new mandate.</strong> The
        organisations that pull ahead are not those with the best models, but
        those with the most refined and governed information environments.
      </p>
    </Callout>

    <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href={url('foundation/')}>The foundation</a>. Seven short pages distilling the model.</li>
      <li><a href={url('commands/')}>The commands</a>. Nine operational moves that put the model to work.</li>
      <li><a href={url('install/')}>Install</a>. One command, every harness.</li>
      <li>
        <a href="https://github.com/IgniticAB/groundwork/blob/main/AI-First%20R%26D%20Context%20Engineering%20101.md">
          AI-First R&amp;D Context Engineering 101.md
        </a>.
        The first source, with references.
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="https://github.com/IgniticAB/groundwork/blob/main/AI%20Agent%20Context%20Engineering%20Best%20Practices.md">
          AI Agent Context Engineering Best Practices.md
        </a>.
        The second source, with references.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>

